{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:13:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:13:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13047"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13047"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.07,0.57,0.2,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76464"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5484"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13047"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61961"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6970"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9319"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9479"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76464"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of severe epigastric pain radiating to her back, associated with vomiting. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension, for which she takes insulin and atenolol. She drinks several glasses of wine on weekends but does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 136/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her BMI is 28 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. There is marked epigastric tenderness with mild jaundice. Bowel sounds are diminished.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important determinant of mortality in acute pancreatitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Age","Diabetes mellitus","Organ dysfunction","Hypocalcaemia","Dehydration"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of acute pancreatitis. The assessment of severity in acute pancreatitis is crucial for appropriate triage and management. Multiple scoring systems exist, but the presence of organ dysfunction has consistently been shown to be the most important prognostic factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrgan dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important determinant of mortality in acute pancreatitis. Persistent organ failure (lasting \u0026gt;48 hours) defines severe acute pancreatitis and carries a mortality rate of 30-50%. The most commonly affected organ systems are respiratory (acute respiratory distress syndrome), cardiovascular (shock), and renal (acute kidney injury).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge\u003C/strong\u003E, while a factor in various prognostic scoring systems like APACHE II, is not the most critical determinant of mortality. Advanced age may impact physiological reserve but does not independently predict poor outcomes to the same degree as organ dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E may complicate the management of acute pancreatitis through effects on glucose homeostasis and increased infection risk, but it is not the primary determinant of mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypocalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in acute pancreatitis due to fat saponification and is included in Ranson\u0027s criteria, but it is not as strongly predictive of mortality as organ dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDehydration\u003C/strong\u003E is common in acute pancreatitis and requires aggressive fluid resuscitation, but the presence of organ dysfunction is a more significant predictor of poor outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Organ failure is the most important determinant of mortality in acute pancreatitis.","Early recognition of organ dysfunction in acute pancreatitis is critical for risk stratification and management planning.","The presence of organ failure for \u003E48 hours defines severe acute pancreatitis."],"references":["Sternby H, Bolado F, Canaval-Zuleta HJ, et al. Determinants of Severity in Acute Pancreatitis: A Nation-wide Multicenter Prospective Cohort Study. Ann Surg. 2019; 270:348-55. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29672416/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61961"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13047"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61961"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T14:23:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T14:23:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5484"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76464"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationshi